comment:
I love how excited you are to see Bjørn experience every single thing for the first time,  and to recognize what a privilege it is for you as a dad to be able to have that much time with him to witness all of it. The world absolutely needs more dads like you,  who are openly trying to figure it out as they go along and worrying first what's best for the child. 

I know there are people who will say you're exploiting your son by using him for content without his consent,  that the creepy people will have access to him for nefarious reasons and blah blah blah. But you're famous anyway,  I mean,  I'm 61 and I knew who you were and I'm not exactly your target audience 🤣. People are going to find you and your family irl regardless,  and probably take pictures.  I'm personally more comfortable with you showing Bjørn in a wholesome and controlled environment than seeing some weirdo posting candids on a "fan account. "

Enjoy the next 18 years with your little family,  as you watch your baby become an amazing,  completely unique and complicated human being.  You and his beautiful mum should be infinitely proud of what you've created. ❤

comment:
The truth is that multilingual families have much more successful children on average. There’s a huge myth out there that it will make them fall behind to learn more than one language at a time. The reality is that if the child is getting deliberate and accurate immersion in said languages, they will do better than their peers in school by the end of elementary.

The problem comes with lack of consistency. Say, one or both parents switching languages, or the parents are not expecting the child to respond in the language directly spoken to them, or the child is expected to respond in the language of a parent they hardly interact enough with. That creates confusion and uncertainty. 

Otherwise, language immersion is fantastic for children. It’s why such established programs exist all over the world and is growing in the US.

comment:
4:30 On the screen time thing, I did zero screen time with my oldest until she was two and my youngest sister went to school for early childhood development and learned something really interesting about screen time with kids and why it is so bad for them. The way that we transmit images through a screen reacts with our brains in a particular way. It's the same phenomena that makes it difficult to fall asleep after watching screens. The way that affects a child's brain is effectively like a drug. The screen is giving them a endorphin (or it might have been dopamine, i get those mixed up XP) high while the screen is on. And then as soon as you turn it off, their body processes that so quickly that they tend to go through a mini withdrawal.

That's why often times when kids get too much screen time, you notice it because they're constantly going through that withdrawal process and acting like little terrors. It's really fascinating, but also really frightening how unnatural this technology is and what it does to our brains, especially as kids.

comment:
10:54 My Niece saved my arse one day when dandering around n babbling/chatting, to the shop, just from a mispronounced word. I think, walking along with a wee toddler, you do start to babble stuff ya normally just keep as 'everyday thoughts' "well mum didn't like our shoes eh? might need to change em? what do you think?" 
like dad's have these convos with their wee ones all the time! It helps actually kinda sort your own inner thinking but out better, since your speaking out loud, to a kid that knows 'ah, ba' 'hoose' and 'ugg', your kinda doing a unique self-therapy at the same time and they will save your ass some time lol

- i remember walking to the shops with my nieces and one had just started her words, we got out stuff, walking out. comment:
Here's another advice from someone who grew up in a bilingual family. Speak to Bjorn in all the languages you want him to know at some point. Do it intermediately. I spoke russian, lithuanian and polish like a native at age 3. My dad fed my absorbing sponge brain russian and polish, he spoke it to me when I wasn't still able to reply, he also watched the beautiful and sweet soviet cartoons. (As bad as the soviet regime was, there was still a lot of not so bad things, and that this the wholesome animations) Mom spoke to me in lithuanian, but I also often observed dad and mom converse in russian and polish. When time came for me to speak, I was fluently using all 3 languages. We lived in a village, so I knew the preferred language of neighbours and spoke it with that particular person. English also came easily at around 5. I watched the English cartoon channels and come first grade I was an ace. 
With babies it usually fairly easy, all babies brains are like sponges. They absorb information, whether they want to or not. They pick up on languages automatically.

comment:
I've been raised bilingual, my parents speaking different languages to me was probably best. How you described you with Swedish, Marzia with Italian, both with English,  then and maybe Japanese out in public would be good. 
My mom spoke to me in spanish and she'd take me to see her other spanish speaking friends and bring me to Mexico from a young age. My dad spoke to me in english and english is the main spoken language where I live.
I think if a parent speaks to the kid in their best language/mother tongue, they get to listen to each language properly (e.g. learning my dad's native english vs my mom's broken english and vice versa) and it'll be easier to contextualise the languages into separate things since they're coming from separate people/environments.

comment:
わぁ、日本語の質問まで答えてくれて！！✨
日本語も上達しましたね！

私も、日本で子育てする親の1人です。
私も夫も日本人ですが、その私達ですら、「どこで子育てするのが、私達、子ども達にとって、一番良いのか？」ということを、毎日毎日毎日考えています。
日本国内だけでも、4か所に住みました。その中には東京もあれば、地方もあります。
なんていうか、場所の違いによって、民度も違うし、気候も違うし、合う合わない（日本語の言い回しで、場所が合わない事を「水が合わない」と言ったりします）もあったりして、難しいです。
でも、なんていうか、人との出会いかなー、と思うことが最近多いです。
あとは、食が合うかどうか。日本国内でも、さまざまな食の違いがあるので、それによっても合う合わないありますね。
Pewdiepie が、家族みんなが、合う場所はどこでしょうね。とにかく人と触れ合ってみることを、おすすめします。
日本語は、他言語話者にとっては難しいのですが、とても自由度が高くて、でも小さなニュアンスまでもが表現できたりする、面白い言語です。
日本に住んでいるうちに、沢山話して、その面白さに気付いてもらえたら、嬉しいです。
あと、災害時に不安というのは、とても分かります。日本は自然災害も多いので。日本の携帯キャリアのスマホは契約していますか？docomo、ソフトバンク、au、それぞれに災害情報を伝えるサービスや機能が備わっています。もちろん、英語でも確認することができます。ぜひ、それらを使うことをおすすめしたいです。

これからも、同じ日本で子育てする者として、応援しています〜！👍

replies: [{'username': '@Ihavenoidea-i3b', 'comment': 'Same thing happened to me! My parents never cared if I spoke in English and they always spoke to me in Spanish. I understand the language i grew up with Karay-ah and Hiligaynon but I can't speak them fluently.", 'date': '2024-10-23T17:52:56Z'}, {'username': '@SpiderDibs', 'comment': "Yep!! You learn it but you don’t know every word in english unless you actively look up words you don’t know or have someone explain it to you. You go to english class and you get corrected and learn. comment: The thing about "soft parenting" is that it's a tool, like any other parenting style it has it's place and it works better in some circumstances than others. The problem that a lot of these soft millennial parents have is they use it at inappropriate times and they don't escalate. Starting from a place of understanding and discussion is a good practice, but when that stops working you need to bring the hammer down. Ultimately, I think a lot of millennial parents treat their kids like peers, but they're not your peers, you're their parent, it's up to you to keep them safe, to teach them how to live in the world, to make them functional human beings, basically.

comment:
My five year old is my forever baby. She’s special needs because of Batten Disease CLN1 and nonverbal. We’ve discovered she prefers a lot of older cartoons like Disney’s Robin Hood and The Rescuers. She likes newer stuff like Moana too, but too much new stuff wears her out so we play a lot of older stuff in between. Absolutely cannot put Cocomelon or Dino Ranchers on though. It’s easier to notice in a special needs child with epilepsy but I’m sure it’s as bad for healthier children too.

Bluey, Blue’s Clues (the one with Steve) and Bear in the Big Blue house are all really great. On a side note, currently her most favorite thing isn’t even cartoons. It’s the bouncy school bus she’s been riding on with her nurse since she started kindergarten!

Anyway, welcome to the parent club 😄 Your son is adorable!

comment:
One thing I would like to share about Björn learning multiple languages is to ensure he also actively engages in either your, Marzia's or both of your's cultures and that he is "integrated" into them. Something I personally don't see talked much about is third-culture children/people and how they grow up in several countries/cultures other than their own. Being one myself, I often struggled integrating with my classmates growing up. I still managed fine and made long-lasting friends, not to mention the perks of seeing cultures from an outside view, and being able to adapt to different people/languages, but I'd be lying if I said I understood my identity. Loneliness wasn't uncommon, as I felt I couldn't relate to most children (culturally) and instead spent most of my time observing/learning from them as an outsider

I understand this now after going through it, but looking back to my younger self, I feel sorry for that confused child who longed for some kind of connection. Not saying this is guaranteed to happen, but it's something I would like to share. Not just to Pewds but for other future parents as well 🙏
cleaned_comment: One thing I would like to share about Björn learning multiple languages is to ensure he also actively engages in either your Marzias or both of yours cultures and that he is integrated into them Something I personally dont see talked much about is thirdculture childrenpeople and how they grow up in several countriescultures other than their own Being one myself I often struggled integrating with my classmates growing up I still managed fine and made longlasting friends not to mention the perks of seeing cultures from an outside view and being able to adapt to different peoplelanguages but Id be lying if I said I understood my identity Loneliness wasnt uncommon as I felt I couldnt relate to most children culturally and instead spent most of my time observinglearning from them as an outsider I understand this now after going through it but looking back to my younger self I feel sorry for that confused child who longed for some kind of connection Not saying this is guaranteed to happen but its something I would like to share Not just to Pewds but for other future parents as well

comment:
He'll pick Japanese up living there and going to school.

Swedish, English and Italian will be the ones you have to work on I imagine. Definitely a difficult to balance, and how to do it in a way that isn't confusing. I'm sure it will work out just fine.

One thing you do hear about is that kids in that environment tend to stick to one or two languages more than the others, so I think it might be good to measure your expectations or don't get too disappointed if he doesn't really gel with Swedish or Italian as he gets older.

Also kids are a product of their environment and school and where they live and when he gets school friends is going to be a huge influence, and based on Japanese society, he's likely to be native level Japanese with a strong desire to learn English like other Japanese young people.

comment:
I mean this in the most positive way possible. The bar for “a good father” has been set so low historically through previous generations that the emergence of social media has made fathers look like super dads by simply existing, participating and sharing. However I think that it’s necessary to share and speak about fatherhood to remove that low bar and make men comfortable to speak about their role and decisions surrounding having a baby. There has always been magazines, tv-shows and profiles discussing motherhood which has in some ways always made the topic present in females lives. Felix wanting to share and discuss fatherhood to his broad audience allows a space for men to open up about the discussion of parenting. 
Of course it’s not necessary to make a big deal about it and make parallels towards men speaking about parenthood but I still think it should be celebrated for the overall topic of parenthood within couples where the role of research and discussion mostly have been given to women historically. 
I as many grew up watching Felix, my partner did it too. I’ve consumed motherhood media consciously and unconsciously for years whilst this is one of few my partner has watched ever. 
Parenthood affects both parents, therefore I’m so glad that the discussion is more and more visible and available for fathers today. Partially thanks to you Felix. You alone helps raise the bar for fathers and how it’s actually fun to be one which previous media hasn’t always portrayed it to be.
Loved this video, take care and thank you

comment:
I don't think this message will be seen... BUT, both myself and my brother grew up in the exact same situation as Bjorn will. Which is, Dad spoke to us in 1 language, Mom spoke to us in another language, they spoke between each other in English, and we lived in a country that spoke a 4th language. So we grew up speaking 4 "native" languages without too much of a problem :)

And now with my wife we have a similar case with out kid, but with 3 languages instead of 4. He's 8 now and speaks these 3 languages basically fully fluently.

People often underestimate what neuroplasticity of kids can accomplish :)

comment:
My kid is the same age as yours, born on the 25th of june 2023. I think it's also important to say that every kid is different. My kiddo had cramps since 4 weeks old till he was about 6/7 months old. He wasnt an affectionate baby, he was more of the " i can do it myself but i can't " kind of kid. He didnt like to snuggle or get calm by anyone. The constant crying, us not knowing what we did wrong, couldnt go away for a few hours without him and getting called to come back because they didnt know what to do, multiple appointments with doctors because he just constantly screamed, the tv could be a lifesaver if we just wanted 15 minutes of rest❤ 

Now that he is getting big and more intrested in things, we took the tv mostly away, unless he gets to cranky. Mine doesnt speak yet, he is trying, but all that comes out is DA DA DA, DIE DIE DIE, HUSSSH. Waiting for the day he will say his first full word tho ❤

comment: I used to grow up with tech myself, although it was still a bit more regulated than being shoved onto the wide web. As my parents wanted to keep it a bit safer for us we mainly had Nintendo consoles and the first I had was a Nintendo DSi with an R4 card with pirated games. But yes, that's how I grew up.

comment:
Just giving some insight on the learning multiple languages thing
As a very young kid I lived in a number of countries but my parents were french and spoke french
In the house we'd speak french and outside I'd speak whatever language was spoken outside
I did start speaking a little later than most but nothing too alarming
Also it did lead me to speak the other languages with any strangers, even on vacation in France, so when they talked to me in French I would answer in another language lmao
Some of those languages I've forgotten since because I moved out when I was young though
Also my mom taught me how to read and write french
When I moved back to France I had the same language level as the rest of my classmates but could also speak fluently other languages
So I'm not too worried about Björn's language learning

comment: Like many others, I grew up watching Pewds. I vividly remember moving out for university; it was a bigger city, and I was on my own. Yet, I always found comfort in watching Felix it felt like having a familiar face around. Funny enough, my name is Felix too, roughly the same age and from a country close to Sweden. Now, with my own son Oskar being seven months old, it's been amazing to see Felix navigating similar experiences and thoughts with Björn; he's always just one step ahead. comment:
After spending my tweens, teens, and early twenties right into the pandemic having to co-parent and babysit my sister's 4 kids, I knew once Pewds had his first child he'd change his tune about them lol. 

One thing I'll say though is that It's such a privilege to be financially stable enough to have both parents stay at home and raise a child. The mental and physical exhaustion of having to work a job or jobs and stress about money and providing everything for your family and also missing out on raising your kids because of working so much is one of the reasons why a lot of parents have such a hard time. Nowadays, at least in America, both parents (if they are still together), have to work to afford the cost of living and the kid gets put in daycare for 9 hours a day (or in my case a family member is forced to take care of them and not have a life of their own) 
Björn is a lucky kid and I wish nothing but the best for you and your beautiful family!

comment: In japan there are "international" schools like the ones you mentioned where Japanese kids go to learn english, but there are also real international schools where they teach in english, mostly everybody there speaks english as their primary language, and obviously they have japanese lessons. I went to one of those until high school and honestly I think it is a nice environment to develop a global awareness but still stay in touch with Japanese culture. From my observations though, kids with non-japanese parents who went to my international school didn't become completely fluent in Japanese, so the Japanese lessons at the school obviously may not be enough. If you wish to make bjorn fluent in japanese, i think sending him to a japanese kindergarten/elementary school before transferring him to an international school is an option. In fact some of my friends at my international school did that and they were fluent in both japanese and english. but idk im not a parent or anything but i hope u find this comment helpful

comment:
You sound like the best kind of parent; the kind that sometimes questions yourself and whether you're doing a good job. I was a classroom teacher for 10 years and in that time, the ones whose parents were often doubting themselves and asking me for advice, were actually the best parents with the happiest kids. It sounds like you are just letting your kid be a kid and that's so beautiful to see. Pewtiful even . 😉

I totally agree about balance. As a child I was kept off screens COMPLETELY and although I think it did good things for my developing brain in general, I had trouble as an adult balancing myself. I became so obsessed with gaming and movies that I would forget to sleep. I think if you grow up with a healthy balance of screen time and what I'd call "body time" (exercising, getting sun on your face, eating good food etc.), it becomes easier to maintain that balance as an adult, because you're used to getting both and will notice if you're missing anything. 

I think the way you are already talking to him a lot will make sure he grows up knowing the language really well. I believe the more he hears of a language is what actually matters for learning, because he's soaking up all the words, even if he's not saying many of them yet. The research shows that growing up multilingual makes it very easy for kids to learn new languages AND it makes them really good learners overall. 

You look like you're doing a fantabulous job with being a parent, thank you for sharing ❤

ETA I'm so glad to see the soft parenting getting this kind of a good review. Again, as a teacher, the kids whose parents talked to them like human beings instead of yelling at them, were the most well adjusted, friendliest kids.

comment: Can definitely relate with the sentiment of "having purpose now". I'm a new father, as of right now my daughter is almost 5 months old. Its a completely life changing event. Everything changes! I thought I knew what love felt like when I met the love of my life and my now wife. But somehow, when it finally clicks and you make that connection with your baby, you finally get the true experience of love. For me, it was when she was about 2 months old and I was holding her to my chest she looked at me directly and purposefully in the eyes and smiled. I broke into tears. Its difficult, fun, interesting, and completely humbling to have a baby. It will test you and your partner's relationship the the limit and every time you come out a stronger couple. You will worry and stress about the wellbeing of this precious new life and through that fire you will learn and you will gain confidence . Your capacity for empathy and love expands to a new level as you finally get that perspective of a parent. You can truly step into your parent's shoes and begin to understand them. I'm truly excited to see where life leads me, and I hope for the best for all new parents out there. Its the most worthwhile thing ever.

"Once you have kids, that doesn't mean you automatically know everything there is about being a parent, it's a learning experience. 

And just because you don't have kids, that doesn't mean you don't know anything or have an idea about raising kids or being a parent. We view and observe and remember from how hard our parents raised us. Reflect on that. And don't be afraid to ask for help from family and friends when raising kids, it can make your life easier." 

And I will always remember those wise words from my father.

comment: The language question is a good one. My theory has been that it's better to master your native tongue first, then learn the language of the country you live in. I realized this because I was born in Asia, learned to read and write before my family migrated to an English speaking country. Growing up, I had friends who moved before they learned to read and write and the difference in our mother tongue was staggering. I actually tested this with my own child because I moved back to my country of origin, raised my kid until he was ready to go to school, then migrated to an English speaking country again. He struggled for about a year to pick up English but now he's perfectly bilingual. I have also heard that kids are fine with picking up both languages at the same time but I have yet to see this in practice . It will be interesting to see how it plays out with FOUR!!! languages as in Bjorn's case. It'll be interesting to see if Bjorn becomes more fluent in English or Japanese lol

comment:
*Also, I wish Parents would STOP making it so "complicated" when having a Baby and they wake at night....*
All you have to do is have a large enough bed, you put the baby in the MIDDLE of the Bed with two small pillows on each side, and then when the baby wakes up and needs to be fed, or changed, the mother just rolls over and feeds the baby, and then whomever changes it if that's what's needed.  It does NOT have to be such a "big deal".  Putting baby's in a crib a long way away, or in other rooms etc. is just STUPID.  My system is EASY, makes it much less stressful, and you get more sleep.  3 boys, I proved it.

Then once they can start sleeping more through the night, you put them in a small bed/crib next to your bed, then when they are fully sleeping through, not breastfeeding anymore, you put them in their own room if you have an extra room.  Easy.  It works.  Very low interruption to your life and sleep doing this system.

- pros: not simply speaking English fluently, but learning it academically (this makes a huge difference imo especially from high school onwards); it may be mostly Japanese kids but many will have dual citizenship, and there will be other foreigners, so it will still be a more multicultural, heterogeneous experience; a private American/British education (healthier approach to studies imho); better facilities.
- cons: might be somewhat removed from local culture (unless he hangs out with Japanese Japanese kids), stuck in a kind of international bubble; kids are usually rich and spoiled; expensive tuition.

بسم الله الرحمن الرحيم . 
أدعوكم إلى دين الحق(دين الإسلام). 
سيندم من لا يدخل هذا الدين . 
نحن المسلمون لنا الحياة التي تأتي بعد الموت
إلى المالا نهاية وهي دار الخلود (الجنة). 
فأنصح كل من ليس على دين الإسلام أن يدخل في دين الإسلام فورا . 
في يوم القيامة يأمر الله الملائكة في النفخ في البوق ويموت كل من على وجه الأرض ،ويأمر الملائكة مرة أخرى فينبعث كل من في الأرض إلى مكان يسمى (المحشر)،وكل إنسان في هذا المكان تتسلط عليه الشمس حسب أعماله في الدنيا ،إن كانت أعماله صالحة فيظلل عليه بغيمة باردة،ومن كانت أعماله سيئة فتسلط عليه الشمس على كامل جسده وتكون الشمس قريبة عليه بنسبة قريبة جداً،ويصيب الناس في أرض المحشر الجوع والعطش الشديد، فيذهبون إلى أصحاب النبي محمد لكي يشفعوا للناس ولكنهم يقولون لسنا لها لسنا لها،فيذهبون الناس إلى رسول الله محمد لكي يشفع لهم
فيقبل الله شفاعته ويبدأ العرض على الله تعالى 
نذهب من أرض المحشر إلى العرض فمن كان كافرا في الدنيا فإنه يأخذ صحيفة أعماله في يده اليسرى
ومن كان مسلما وعمله صالح في الدنيا يأخذ صحيفة أعماله بيده اليمنى ،بعد هذه المرحلة تأتي مرحلة الحساب على الأعمال ،فمن كان مسلما وعمله صالح فهو يسلم من النار ،ومن كان كافرا وعمل ليس صالحا فمصيره النار ،ثم بعد مرحلة الحساب نذهب إلى المرور فوف (السّراط المستقيم) وهو حبل نحيف جدا تحته يوجد وادي من أودية جهنم فمن عبر (السّراط المستقيم) فهو في أمان ،ومن يقع عن هذا الحبل فهو في خطر شديد ،ثم بعد هذه المرحلة تأتي مرحلة دخول الناس الجنة أو النار ،الكفار يدخلون جهنم للأبد لا يوجد ماء ولا طعام كلما نمت جلود الكفار في جهنم يبدلون جلودا غيرها وهكذا الحال إلى الأبد مع العذاب الشديد وطعامهم في جهنم يكون الشوك ،وهكذا إلى الأبد،أمّا أصحاب الجنة وهم المسلمون فهم ينعمون في الجنة إلى الأبد ويوجد في الجنة أنهار من كل ما تشتهي الأنفس، وقصور من فضة وذهب ،ولباس من حرير ،وطعام من كل ما تشتهي الأنفس ،أهل الجنة لا يمرضون ،ولا ينزل منهم العرق في الجنة،يكونون في سعادة تامة إلى الأبد ،لا يزدادوا في العمر ،ولا يملون في الجنة ،وهكذا كله إلى الأبد إلى الأبد. 
فتخيل معي يا أخي لما لا تريد أن تصبح مسلما ،كل هذه الخيرات تريد أن تهدرها على نفسك ،أنصحك 
أن تدخل دين الإسلام فهمو الدين الحق ،وهو دين الخلود،والسلام عليكم ورحمة الله وبركاته.

comment:
Hey Felix, 
I've been following your content on YouTube all the way from 2010/11, as a huge fan of yours and just kind of grew along with you.

Just last year on the 2nd of June my little daughter was born, right around the same time as your son. Watching your content now feels so rewarding. It feels like I've made it all this way and finally gotten to a point of rest, where I'm just happy with my life. Fatherhood has been such a blessing. All those sleepless nights and struggles get washed away by the beauty of watching your little one grow up into a happy and healthy little human. 
I'm sure you can agree. 

Following your content and kind of experiencing all of this for the first time, just as you do really helps with all the first time dad-anxiety. 

If you ever read this, I just want to thank you from the bottom of my heart for all these years of content and entertainment, growing alongside you and funnily enough becoming a dad at a simular time. We've had a simular evolution of interests and I could always watch and enjoy your content, never missing a video. 

Especially your more philosophical and thoughtful videos resonated so much with me and this newer form of content/vlog you seem to do mostly for yourself is my favourite by far.

I wish you and your family all the happiness, peace and excitement in the world. You're an incredible dad and a huge inspiration for me as a long time fan.

last time we visited my MiL, my daughter (6) was hunting for four leaf clovers. We walked around their yard, and I found some... usually if you find one (didn't pick it at this point), there are others near it. 

So i had my daughter and MiL come over to where i was, and we hunted there.

My daughter found one of the four leaf clovers and she was so excited. MiL found one too. Ended up being at least 3 in that little patch of clover.

They're pressed in a book at MiL's house currently. Going to tape them with packing tape to 'laminate' them so can keep them forever. 

♥


Anyway, love seeing yall so happy! and the lil' man is growing up so fast.
they all do. 
♥

comment:
This might be my favorite "vlog episode" yet. It has everything:

Björn starting to really interact with everything and everyone around, Italy and its beautiful plains and mountains, the food, the nostalgia hit while going back to that basement where everything started, the friends you made along the way and that are still here to enjoy a treck with you around a lake, the swedes houses, the forest where you can boulder to, your parents taking time to babysit their grandson but also following and helping you bouldering...

It has everything. Family, friends, busy airports, fields, lakes, mountains, forests, rocks, pizza, houses, memories... This may be a pretty "common" way of enjoying various things of life to its fullest, but these vlogs always capture and transcribe those moments so purely it feels genuinely like the best life anyone could have.

I wish to myself, and anyone reading this, that you are, or will someday experience this kind of bliss at least once in your life. Wishing yall the best!
